<h2>LG Dryer Drum Bearing Replacement Cost Breakdown</h2>
<p>The OEM drum bearing assembly for most LG models costs $60-$100 depending on your specific dryer. Labor adds $120-$180 because accessing the bearing requires removing the drum entirely — it's a 90-minute job for our experienced technicians. Total cost runs $200-$350 including parts, labor, and our standard one-year warranty. We waive the $65 diagnostic fee when you approve the repair, so you're not paying extra just to find out what's wrong.</p>
<h3>Why Labor Costs More Than the Part</h3>
<p>Drum bearing replacement is labor-intensive. Our techs need to remove the front panel, disconnect the belt, lift out the drum, press out the old bearing, and install the new one with proper alignment. One degree of misalignment and the bearing fails again within months. That's why professional installation makes financial sense.</p>

<h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Drum Bearing Needs Replacement</h2>
<p>The earliest warning sign is a rhythmic squealing or grinding noise that gets louder over time. You might also notice the drum wobbles slightly when you spin it by hand, or your dryer vibrates more than usual during heavy loads. Some homeowners report a metallic scraping sound — that's the drum shaft rubbing against the worn bearing housing. Don't ignore these symptoms. A failing bearing puts stress on the motor and belt, turning a $200-$350 repair into a $500+ multi-component job if you wait too long.</p>
<h3>How Long Do LG Drum Bearings Last?</h3>
<p>Most LG drum bearings last 5-8 years under normal use. Heavy-load households — families running 8+ loads per week — see bearing wear closer to the 4-5 year mark. Our technicians find that proper vent maintenance extends bearing life because the dryer doesn't have to run as long per cycle.</p>

<h2>DIY vs Professional Drum Bearing Replacement</h2>
<p>You can buy the OEM bearing for $60-$100 online, but we don't recommend DIY installation. The drum weighs 30-40 pounds and requires careful handling to avoid damaging the felt seal or moisture sensors. Our techs use a bearing press tool to ensure proper seating — most homeowners don't have this specialized equipment. We've repaired numerous DIY attempts where the bearing was installed crooked, causing premature failure and drum damage that doubled the repair cost.</p>
<h3>Tools Required for Professional Installation</h3>
<p>Proper bearing replacement requires a bearing press, torque wrench, drum support cradle, and specific socket sizes for LG's fastener patterns. Our technicians carry all necessary equipment for same-day completion.</p>

<h2>OEM vs Aftermarket Drum Bearings</h2>
<p>We exclusively install OEM LG bearings because aftermarket versions use inferior steel alloys that wear out faster. The tolerances on genuine LG bearings are tighter — less wobble means less noise and longer life. We've seen aftermarket bearings fail in under a year, while OEM replacements typically last another 5-7 years. The $15-$20 savings on an aftermarket part isn't worth the hassle of a repeat service call.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>How much does LG dryer drum bearing replacement cost?</h3>
<p>Total cost is $200-$350 including the OEM bearing assembly ($60-$100) and labor ($120-$180). We waive the $65 diagnostic fee when you proceed with repair. The exact price depends on your LG model — DLGX series tends to be at the higher end due to more complex disassembly.</p>
<h3>How long does drum bearing replacement take?</h3>
<p>About 90 minutes for our experienced technicians. The job involves removing the front panel, drum, and old bearing, then pressing in the new bearing and reassembling everything. We run a full test cycle before leaving to verify proper operation.</p>
<h3>Can I keep using my dryer with a bad bearing?</h3>
<p>Technically yes, but we don't recommend it. A worn bearing puts extra strain on the motor and belt, which can cause those components to fail too. What starts as a $200-$350 bearing replacement can become a $500+ repair if the motor burns out from the added resistance.</p>
<h3>How do I know if it's the bearing or the drum rollers?</h3>
<p>Drum rollers typically produce a thumping or rumbling noise, while a bad bearing creates a high-pitched squeal or grinding sound from the rear of the dryer. Our technicians test both during diagnosis — sometimes both need replacement on older units.</p>
<h3>Do you warranty the bearing replacement?</h3>
<p>Yes, every bearing replacement includes our standard one-year warranty on parts and labor. If the same bearing fails within the warranty period, we'll return and fix it at no charge.</p>

